e, he details the way in which escalation could occur not by mindless accident, or by deliberate preference for nuclear escalation, but rather as a natural accompaniment of land, naval, or air warfare at the conventional level. Posen bases his analysis on an empirical study of the east-west military competition in Europe during the 1980s, using a conceptual framework drawn from international relations theory, organization theory, and strategic theory.The lessons of his book, however, go well beyond the east-west competition. Since his observations are relevant to all military competitions between states armed with both conventional and nuclear weaponry, his book speaks to some of the problems that attend the proliferation of nuclear weapons in longstanding regional conflicts. Optimism that small and medium nuclear powers can easily achieve "stable" nuclear balances is, he believes, unwarranted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEscalation (Military science). 0aLimited war. 0aNuclear threshold (Strategy). 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aInternational Relations.  aNuclear Risks.  aPolitical Science.  aSecurity Affairs .  aSecurity studies .  aStudies in Security Affairs.  aThe Sources of Military Doctrine.  aarms control .  adynamics of escalation.  aglobal nuclear warfare .  aintensification of conflict.  ainternational security .  ainternational security issues .  alimited war .  amilitary escalation .  amilitary policy .  amilitary science .  amilitary strategy .  amilitary studies .  amutually assured destruction .  anuclear Armageddon .  anuclear defenses .  anuclear military war .  anuclear politics .  anuclear revolution .  anuclear risks .  anuclear s